  "answer": "In 'Shikwa' (Bang-E-Dara Part 3, ch. 20), the rhetorical move is performative complaint directed upward — an act of bold apostrophe to God. Iqbal frames the speech self-consciously as transgressive ('Forgive my tongue, but God, I have a grievance to declare'), positioning the Muslim collective as a wronged party presenting a legal petition to the divine court. The argument is structured as a historical quid pro quo: the speaker catalogues Muslims' sacrifices for God's name ('It was we, and we alone, who were Your champions in the fight... we died along the way') and then contrasts this past service with present abandonment ('Is this the prize for those who gave their very lives for Thee?'). The emotion — anger, bewilderment, defiance — is itself deployed as evidence. The mode is dialogic and adversarial: God is directly addressed throughout, implicitly expected to respond.\n\nIn 'Falsafa-e-Gham' (Bang-E-Dara Part 3, ch. 7), the rhetorical move is philosophical distancing. Iqbal steps back from grief altogether to examine its ontological function. There is no direct address to God; the speaker instead makes impersonal, aphoristic observations ('Sorrow is not sorrow, but a silent song of soul'). Grief is reframed as a necessary instrument of spiritual development — it 'polishes' the heart, gives the soul 'wings for flight,' and preserves the beloved through continued presence in memory. The river metaphor (a stream shatters on valley rocks, becomes a thousand pearls, then reforms) performs this logic structurally: fragmentation and sorrow are stages in a larger pattern of reunion. The mode is monologic and consolatory.\n\nThe core rhetorical contrast: in Shikwa, grief is a speech act — it accuses, demands, and awaits reply; the poet wields it outward at God. In Falsafa-e-Gham, grief is a philosophical category — it is accepted, theorized, and transcended; the poet turns it inward as a tool of insight rather than a weapon of address.",
